projects.description:
Wade - is a Yet Another Debugging Window (yadw) - wade looks like an anagram of a "yadw" if you squint really hard, so that's why it's called Wade.

It's yet another debugging window! This is more of an experiment... I embedded the famous DearImGui inside a WinForms element inside a WPF Window! 

How to use:
Go to Developer Menu -> DearImGui Window

And it's an API, so look at the below examples and PR to see its usage.

Here's a screenshot:
![image.png](https://rocscience.visualstudio.com/c5517f3f-c52e-4a50-8a4c-5611a458b9ab/_apis/git/repositories/fc99cf50-c1fb-437d-86bd-33236c171d47/pullRequests/22871/attachments/image.png)

Here's a simple example of making a list box with all the nodes in an RFC project:
```cs
 Wade.Wade.Window("Node Window", null, (object userData) =>
 {
     var workspace = Workspace.This;
     if (workspace == null) return;

     var proj = workspace.ActiveProject as RS3Project;
     if (proj == null) return;

     var geoms = proj.GeomGraph.Nodes.ToArray();
     if (ImGui.BeginListBox("Nodes"))
     {
         for (int i = 0; i < geoms.Length; ++i)
         {
             ImGui.PushID(i);

             if (ImGui.Selectable(geoms[i].Name))
             {

             }

             ImGui.PopID();
         }
     }
     ImGui.EndListBox();
 });
```

Remember this is an immediate mode UI, it re-renders 12 times a second! This means, this list box is updated whenever the `Nodes` array changes. No need to hook up listeners and stuff.

Filtering is as easy as skipping elements in the node list!
```cs
...
for (int i = 0; i < geoms.Length; ++i)
{
    if (geoms[i].Name.StartsWith("Cube")) continue;

    ImGui.PushID(i);

    if (ImGui.Selectable(geoms[i].Name))
    {
    }
    ImGui.PopID();
}
...
```

Here's a gif of playing break-out where the nodes are the bricks! Every time you hit a brick a node gets deleted!!
![imguibreakout.gif](https://rocscience.visualstudio.com/c5517f3f-c52e-4a50-8a4c-5611a458b9ab/_apis/git/repositories/fc99cf50-c1fb-437d-86bd-33236c171d47/pullRequests/22871/attachments/imguibreakout.gif)

I don't know if I'll end up cleaning this up and actually using it. Although, it can be pretty useful if you want a quick debug window with controls that you can easily edit without having to setup an entire debug xaml window and hook up the signals which takes forever and sucks.

The break-out demo is mostly a joke, but it serves to highlight how powerful the imgui API is. You can pretty much draw anything you want! This makes visualizing certain problems a lot easier. You can have sliders, text boxes, radio buttons, etc, and since it updates every frame (12 a second), you never need to worry about data being out of sync.
